<h2><a href="https://uxdesign.cc/lets-talk-neumorphism-and-accessibility-44a48a6ace72">Let&rsquo;s talk Neumorphism and Accessibility</a></h2>
<span><a href="https://vickyvo.me/">Uyen Vicky Vo</a></span>

<p>I always enjoy seeing the development of a new design trend, even if it&rsquo;s something I never plan to use myself. Neumorphism has been floating around quite a lot recently, and seems to have nicely divided opinion. That means lots of discussion pieces talking about the pros and cons of the style, which means lots of stuff for me to read.</p>

<blockquote>

<p>Neumorphism is a play on words based on New + Skeuomorphism. It is a style that uses blur, angle, and intensity of an object&rsquo;s shadow to highlight the object. It&rsquo;s a design that looks realistic, futuristic, modern, appealing and extremely breathtaking due to its soft shadow and overall appearance.</p>

<p>But let&rsquo;s be honest, it&rsquo;s not the most practical design for actual use. Try building and releasing a product that has used <a href="https://uxdesign.cc/neumorphism-in-user-interfaces-b47cef3bf3a6">Neumorphism</a> as its main style, and you&rsquo;re most likely going to frustrate everyone&hellip;</p>

</blockquote>

<p>In this post, Vicky Vo talks about the accessibility issues inherent in a style that tends towards low contrast. As you might expect, there are a lot.</p>

<p>Actually, the more I see of neumorphism, the less I like it.</p>

