<h2><a href="https://sebastiangreger.net/2020/02/bookmark-link-targets-usability-and-accessibility/">Link Targets</a></h2>
<span><a href="https://twitter.com/sebastiangreger">Sebastian Greger</a></span>

<blockquote>

    <p>The only arguments I&rsquo;ve ever heard for opening links in a new tab/window — despite presenting evidence from usability research — came from marketing. And it&rsquo;s always about the goal of an organisation to trick users into &ldquo;keeping them on our site&rdquo;</p>

    <cite><a href="https://twitter.com/sebastiangreger">Sebastian Greger</a>, <a href="https://sebastiangreger.net/2020/02/bookmark-link-targets-usability-and-accessibility/">Link Targets</a></cite>

</blockquote>

<p>The discussion over whether links should be set to open in a new tab/window has been ongoing for years now. Personally, I like links to open where they are, allowing me to choose whether or not to middle-click and open a new tab.</p>

<p>So far I haven&rsquo;t read much research into the usability question (although I will do so now), but I&rsquo;m inclined to agree with Sebastian that the requirement to open links in new tabs usually comes from the marketing side of a business.</p>

