<h2><a href="https://adactio.com/journal/16442">Utopia</a></h2>
<span><a href="https://twitter.com/adactio">Jeremy Keith</a>, <a href="https://adactio.com/journal/16442">Utopia</a></span>

<p>Jeremy Keith posted a quick write up of Utopia, Trys Mudford and James Gilyead&rsquo;s breakpointless fluid typography and spacing project. Both Trys and James work at Clearleft, so Jeremy has an interesting perspective here.</p>

<blockquote>

    <p>The genesis for Utopia came about after Trys and James worked together on a few different projects. It&rsquo;s all too easy to let design and development splinter off into their own caves, but on these projects, Trys and James were working (literally) side by side. This meant that they could easily articulate frustrations to one another, and more important, they could easily share their excitement.</p>

    <p>The end result of their collaboration is some very clever code. There&rsquo;s an irony here. This code could be used to discourage collaboration! After all, why would designers and developers sit down together if they can just pass these numbers back and forth?</p>

    <p>But I don&rsquo;t think that Utopia will appeal to designers and developers who work in that way. Born in the spirit of collaboration, I suspect that it will mostly benefit people who value collaboration.</p>

    <cite><a href="https://twitter.com/adactio">Jeremy Keith</a>, <a href="https://adactio.com/journal/16442">Utopia</a></cite>

</blockquote>

<p>After a succinct breakdown of the project&rsquo;s aims, Jeremy highlights some of the reasons you might want to use it on your own projects.</p>